{
  "root_cause": "The multimodal path shares GPU tensors to the scheduler/TP workers by slicing a shared MmItemMemoryPool and exporting a CUDA/HIP IPC handle for each slice's underlying storage. All slices from the pool are views over the SAME base storage, so every mm item's _share_cuda_() handle points at the same underlying allocation. With SGLANG_USE_IPC_POOL_HANDLE_CACHE left at its default (False), the receiver does not cache/reuse an already-opened mapping for that base allocation: it calls torch.UntypedStorage._new_shared_cuda(...) (hipIpcOpenMemHandle) fresh for every single mm item, and the previously-opened UntypedStorage object (and its hipIpcOpenMemHandle mapping) is dropped/garbage-collected as soon as that item's reconstruction finishes, which closes the IPC mapping (hipIpcCloseMemHandle) for the whole base allocation. Under concurrency (128 concurrent MMMU requests), many in-flight reconstructions on TP workers are using pointers derived from that same base mapping at once; when one request's transient open/close cycle finishes and closes the mapping, every other concurrently-in-flight reconstruction that is still dereferencing a pointer into that same base allocation now holds a stale/freed device pointer, producing 'Failed to deserialize from CUDA IPC handle (HIP error: invalid device pointer)' and crashing the TP scheduler process (SIGQUIT/child failure).",
  "fix": "Set SGLANG_USE_IPC_POOL_HANDLE_CACHE=1 (in addition to the existing SGLANG_USE_CUDA_IPC_TRANSPORT=1) in launch_qwen3.5_27b_sglang.sh. This makes the sender pass the mm-feature pool's own IPC handle (pool_ipc_handle) to CudaIpcTensorTransportProxy, and makes the receiver open that base pool allocation's IPC handle exactly once and cache the resulting UntypedStorage in _pool_storage_cache (see cuda_ipc_transport_utils.py: _pool_handle_cache_get_or_open / _pool_storage_cache), reusing it (by byte-offset slicing) for every subsequent mm item instead of repeatedly opening and closing the mapping. This keeps the CUDA IPC multimodal transport enabled while eliminating the concurrent open/close race that produced stale device pointers.",
  "evidence": "Line ~3614-3647 of crash_qwen3.5-27b-mmmu-con128.log: '[TP1] Failed to deserialize from CUDA IPC handle (HIP error: invalid device pointer' raised from python/sglang/srt/utils/cuda_ipc_transport_utils.py:488 in reconstruct_on_target_device, immediately followed by 'torch.AcceleratorError: HIP error: invalid device pointer' and '[2026-07-16 12:50:59] SIGQUIT received. ... It usually means one child failed.', occurring during the MMMU vision forward pass (vision.py:396 -> qwen3_vl.py get_image_feature -> mm_utils.py embed_mm_inputs) under concurrency=128."
}

